Kinesis Data Streams.

When data must feed multiple downstream consumers, each at its own pace, with the ability to rewind and replay history, that's a stream, not a queue. Kinesis Data Streams is the AWS-native streaming service. Producers push records into a stream; multiple consumers read them at their own pace; and records are retained in the stream for up to a year. The difference from S-Q-S is the whole point. S-Q-S is a work queue: each message is processed by one consumer and then deleted. Kinesis is a stream: records stay in the stream after consumption, multiple consumers can read the same data independently, and consumers can rewind and replay. S-Q-S is the right shape for asynchronous jobs; Kinesis is the right shape for telemetry, clickstreams, I-o-T, and change-capture, anything where the data has multiple downstream consumers or has to be reprocessed.

A stream is divided into shards, the unit of capacity. Each shard supports one megabyte per second or a thousand records per second on write, and two megabytes per second on read, shared across all standard consumers. You scale by adding shards, called splitting, or removing them, called merging. Every record carries a partition key that Kinesis hashes to pick a shard, so the same key always lands on the same shard and is ordered within it; choose a high-cardinality key to spread the load, exactly like the hot-partition lesson in DynamoDB.

There are two consumer models with very different throughput. Standard consumers poll with get-records and share the shard's two-megabyte read budget, so five consumers each get four hundred kilobytes a second, at about two hundred milliseconds latency. Enhanced Fan-Out, or E-F-O, gives each consumer its own dedicated two megabytes per second via H-T-T-P-two push, at about seventy milliseconds latency; it costs more but is the right pick when several consumers each need full throughput. The rule: one or two consumers where cost matters, use standard; many consumers or low-latency push, use E-F-O.
